This article is a presidential proclamation by Barack Obama in 2011, celebrating the 40th anniversary of the 26th Amendment to the United States Constitution. The amendment lowered the voting age from 21 to 18, giving millions of young Americans the right to vote. The proclamation acknowledges the hard work and advocacy that went into achieving this amendment, and highlights the importance of young people's voices in shaping the country. The article also mentions various initiatives launched by the Obama Administration to engage young Americans in the political process and encourage their involvement in creating positive change. The proclamation calls upon all Americans to participate in ceremonies and activities honoring young Americans and those who have fought for freedom and justice in the country.